import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;

public class Main {
    public static String wrapNonATagContent(String input) {
        String[] parts = input.split("(<a>|</a>)");
        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = 0; i < parts.length; i++) {
            if (i % 2 == 0) {
                result.append("<b>").append(parts[i]).append("</b>");
            } else {
                result.append("<a>").append(parts[i]).append("</a>");
            }
        }
        return result.toString();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input = "Hello <a>World</a>!";
        String expected = "<b>Hello </b><a>World</a><b>!</b>";
        assertEquals(expected, wrapNonATagContent(input));
    }
}
```

This code uses a regular expression to split the input string into parts based on the `<a>` and `</a>` tags. It then iterates over the parts and wraps the non-tag parts with `<b>` tags. The `main` method demonstrates the usage of the `wrapNonATagContent` function with the test case provided in the question.<step> Source: assistant
